A photo of the Ryan NYP &quot;Spirit of St. Louis&quot; at Curtiss Field (adjacent to Roosevelt Field) on Long Island, after the replacement of the original nose cone.

Standing from left to right are, B.F. Mahoney, Harry F. Guggenheim, Lindbergh, and Charles Lawrance.

Mahoney was the owner of Ryan Airlines, the builders of the &quot;Spirit of St. Louis.&quot;  

Guggenheim, a wealthy buinessman and philanthropist from the North Shore of Long Island, had just met Lindbergh.  After Lindbergh's triumphant return to the US, he and Guggenheim would assist the work of another aviation pioneer, Robert F. Goddard.

Lawrance was an aeronautical engineer who was instrumental in the development of the air-cooled radial engine.  His own company, the Lawrance Aero Engine Company, was purchased by Wright Aeronautical in 1923.  In 1925, Lawrance would become the president of Wright Aeronautical and lead the development of the Wright J-5 Whirlwind that powered the &quot;Spirit of St. Louis.&quot;
